---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="The MoE Router Scores Experts Per Token">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L24" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">How does the router choose experts?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        A Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) layer replaces the single FFN with several smaller FFNs called <strong>experts</strong>. Not every expert runs for every token. A small network called the <strong>router</strong> decides which experts each token should use.
      </p>
      <p>
        The router is a simple linear projection: it takes the token's hidden state and produces one score (a <strong>router logit</strong>) per expert. These logits measure how relevant each expert is for this particular token.
      </p>
      <p>
        The logits are then passed through softmax (or sigmoid, depending on the architecture) to get <strong>gating weights</strong>. Why not just pick the top-k logits directly? Because the gating weights serve double duty: they select which experts to run <em>and</em> they determine how much each expert's output contributes to the final result. Softmax ensures the weights sum to 1, so the combined output is a proper weighted average — not an arbitrarily scaled sum.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each token may pick a different set of experts. This is what makes MoE "sparse": the model has many total parameters (all the experts), but each token only activates a small subset. A model with 64 experts and top-2 routing uses only about 3% of its expert parameters per token — so it can be very large in parameter count while keeping per-token compute manageable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          4 experts, top-2 selection. Router logits for one token:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">logits:</span> &nbsp; [2.1, &nbsp;0.3, &nbsp;3.5, &nbsp;-0.8]
          </div>
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">softmax:</span> [0.19, 0.03, <span style="color: var(--sem-router);">0.77</span>, 0.01] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(sum = 1.0, approx.)</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span style="color: var(--sem-router);">top-2:</span> Expert 2 (weight 0.77), Expert 0 (weight 0.19)
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          Experts 1 and 3 are not activated for this token. They do zero work.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Hidden state per token: [d_model]</div>
        <div>Router weight matrix: [d_model, n_experts]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-router);">Router logits per token: [n_experts]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">After gating: top-k indices and their normalized weights.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-router);">logits = x &middot; W_router &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// [d_model] &middot; [d_model, n_experts] &rarr; [n_experts]</span></div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-router); margin-top: var(--space-2);">gates = softmax(logits) &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">// or sigmoid(logits)</span></div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">selected = top_k(gates, k)</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, the router is a linear layer whose output dimension equals the number of experts. The gating function (softmax or sigmoid) and top-k value are model hyperparameters. You will see this in <code>build_moe_ffn()</code>.
        </p>
        <div class="file-path">src/llama-graph.cpp &mdash; build_moe_ffn()</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The router itself is cheap — a single matrix-vector multiply. The cost that matters is what happens next: only <em>k</em> of <em>n</em> experts run. If a model has 64 experts and top-2 routing, each token uses 2/64 = about 3.1% of the expert parameters. The total parameter count is large, but the active compute per token is small.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L24"
        gateStrength="hard"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L24-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Given router logits [1.0, 4.0, 0.5, 3.0] and top-2 selection, which experts are chosen?',
            tag: 'math',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Expert 0 and Expert 2', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Expert 1 and Expert 3', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Expert 0 and Expert 1', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The two highest logits are at index 1 (4.0) and index 3 (3.0). After softmax these remain the two largest, so top-2 selects Expert 1 and Expert 3.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L24-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'What is the shape of the router output for a single token if the model has 16 experts?',
            tag: 'shape',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: '[d_model]', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: '[16]', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: '[16, d_model]', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The router produces one logit per expert. With 16 experts, the output is a vector of 16 scores.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
